  <h1>PR and press for architects</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Press is one of the most powerful things a firm can own and one of the worst
    things to build a growth plan on. The whole game is knowing which job it actually
    does, and it is not the job most firms chase it for.
  </p>

  <p>
    Getting published on the biggest architecture site in the world puts your work in
    front of something like eighteen million readers a month. Almost none of whom will
    ever hire you, because almost all of them are other architects. It is a magnificent
    trophy handed out at a party your clients were never invited to.
  </p>
  <p>
    So press is not useless. It is misfiled. Firms reach for it as a way to get found,
    which it is terrible at, when its real value is something else entirely: a way to be
    believed once someone has already found you. Get that backwards and you spend a year
    chasing bylines and wonder why the phone stays quiet.
  </p>

  <div class="answer">
    <p class="answer-label">The short answer</p>
    <p>Press and awards are a proof layer, not a lead engine. Earned media is the most trusted form of promotion there is, but design-press readers are your peers, not your buyers. So aim residential stories at local and consumer outlets, commercial ones at business press, use the coverage as credibility your ads and proposals point at, collect the backlink, and let the engine that creates demand do the finding.</p>
  </div>
  <p>
    This page is about where press and awards actually sit in the wider system of <a href="/architecture-marketing">architecture marketing</a>, and, more usefully, where they do not. Because it is a genuinely good asset, held wrong-end-first by nearly everyone who reaches for it.
  </p>

  <h2>The one distinction that decides everything</h2>
  <p>
    The press that impresses your peers and the press your buyer reads are two different
    mastheads. Winning the first feels far better and does far less. Firms spend years
    confusing them, then frame the award and go back to wondering where the work is.
  </p>
  <p>
    ArchDaily, Dezeen, the design annuals, the AIA honors, they are all real credentials
    and worth having as proof of your craft. But the homeowner planning a renovation and
    the developer picking a firm for a forty-unit build have never once opened them. That
    audience is architects and students admiring each other's sections. Lovely company.
    None of it is a client.
  </p>
  <p>
    A trade feature is a peer signal and a portfolio line. Treat it as exactly that and
    it earns its place. Treat it as a marketing plan and you have built your growth on
    the approval of the only people in the market who are never going to pay you.
  </p>

  <h2>What press actually buys you</h2>
  <p>
    One thing, and it is worth a lot: borrowed credibility. Nielsen has measured trust in
    advertising across dozens of countries for over a decade, and the same result holds
    every time. Earned media, a real third party vouching for you, is the most trusted
    form there is. A genuine news article is trusted by roughly two thirds of people, far
    more than anything a firm says about itself.
  </p>
  <p>
    That is the one thing you cannot buy, write, or fake. Anyone can claim they are the
    best firm in the city. A journalist or an awards jury saying a version of it is
    believed in a way your own website never will be, because the person saying it has
    nothing to sell.
  </p>
  <p>
    So the value of press is proof, not reach. It is something a buyer who is already
    weighing you up can find, check, and trust. It makes your <a href="/website-design-for-architects">website</a> more convincing, your proposals heavier, and every other thing you run land harder. It closes the gap between interested and convinced. What it does not do is open that gap in the first place.
  </p>

  <h2>The two buyers read two completely different mastheads</h2>
  <p>
    If press is going to reach a buyer at all rather than just your peers, you have to
    aim it, and the two halves of the market read nothing in common. Pick the buyer
    before you pick the outlet.
  </p>

  <h3>If you do residential work</h3>
  <p>
    The homeowner who will hire you is not on ArchDaily. They are reading local. The city
    magazine's list of favorite architects, the regional paper's home and design section,
    a before-and-after feature in a shelter publication, the neighborhood glossy that runs
    a piece on a renovation two streets over.
  </p>
  <p>
    That is the press worth chasing here, because it is the press that actually reaches the
    person about to start a project. Reaching them where they already look is the whole job in <a href="/marketing-for-residential-architects">marketing for residential architects</a>, and a warm local story does it in a way no peer award can.
  </p>

  <h3>If you do commercial work</h3>
  <p>
    Forget the design annuals entirely. Your buyer is a developer, a business owner, or a
    facilities director, and they read business press, not architecture press. The regional
    business journal, the trade publication of their own industry rather than yours, a
    bylined piece where you sound like someone who understands their timeline and their
    budget rather than their taste.
  </p>
  <p>
    A short, considered placement in the right business outlet does real work over a long
    sales cycle, because it gives a cautious buyer something credible to find while they
    quietly decide. The full commercial picture is in <a href="/marketing-for-commercial-architects">marketing for commercial architects</a>, and press is the third-party proof layer inside it.
  </p>

  <h2>How to earn it without a six-thousand-a-month publicist</h2>
  <p>
    Most firms assume press means hiring an agency and hoping. You can earn a surprising
    amount of it yourself if you stop pitching yourself and start being useful to the
    people who write the stories.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Be a source, not a press release. Reporters need expert quotes on deadline constantly. The free tool everyone used for this, HARO, shut down at the end of 2024 and came back under new owners in 2025, and live tools like Qwoted and Featured do the same job: they connect you to journalists actively looking for someone who knows your subject. Answer the ones in your lane and get quoted.</li>
    <li>Bring something only you have. "Local firm completes house" is a story no one runs. A real opinion, a local angle, or a number nobody else has ("why the new zoning rewrite will change what your street looks like") is a story an editor actually wants.</li>
    <li>Use awards as proof, not as a plan. Enter the ones your buyer would recognize or that make a strong line in a proposal, then put them on your site. The trophy is not a pipeline, it is a credential you display to the pipeline you built elsewhere.</li>
    <li>Keep it small and human. A short list of local, sector, and trade journalists you actually know beats a blast to five hundred inboxes that all delete it. Press is a relationship, run at the scale of relationships.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The quiet bonus that outlasts the article</h2>
  <p>
    There is a second payoff most firms miss. When a real publication writes about you, it
    usually links to you, and a link and a brand mention from a trusted outlet are among the
    strongest off-page signals you can earn in search. The clipping ages; the link keeps
    working for years.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is where press and search quietly overlap, and it is why a coverage push doubles as a ranking push. How that compounding layer works, and why it pays you back long after publication, is the whole of <a href="/seo-for-architects">SEO for architects</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Where press stops</h2>
  <p>
    Here is the ceiling, and it is the same one every proof channel has. Press cannot be
    scheduled or scaled. You cannot decide on a Tuesday that you want thirty qualified
    inquiries and produce a magazine feature by Friday, and even if you could, most of the
    people reading it are the wrong people. It builds trust. It does not create demand.
  </p>
  <p>
    Which is exactly why it belongs on top of the thing that does create demand, rather than in place of it. The channel that puts your work in front of the actual buyer, on a schedule you control, for both residential and commercial firms, is paid social, and the case for it is in <a href="/meta-ads-for-architects">Meta ads for architects</a>. That is the engine. Press is the proof the engine gets to point at.
  </p>
  <p>
    Picture the two together. Your ads put your work in front of the right buyer and capture
    the ones ready to raise a hand. The interested-but-cautious ones go and Google you before
    they book, and there they find the feature, the award, the coverage, and the story flips
    from "some firm ran an ad" to "the firm the local paper wrote about."
  </p>
  <p>
    (The first thing that brand search shows them is your profile, covered in <a href="/google-business-profile-for-architects">Google Business Profile for architects</a>.) How the full pipeline connects is in <a href="/lead-generation-for-architects">lead generation for architects</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>A few honest answers</h2>
  <h3>Should I hire a PR agency?</h3>
  <p>
    A good one that earns you real coverage in outlets your buyer actually reads is worth it,
    as a proof layer. Just do not sign a retainer expecting a pipeline out of it. Generating
    inquiries on a schedule is the engine's job, not the publicist's, and confusing the two is
    how firms burn a year and a budget.
  </p>
  <h3>Is an ArchDaily feature worth chasing?</h3>
  <p>
    As a credential and a peer signal, yes, it is a real thing to be proud of and good proof to
    display. As a way to reach clients, no, because clients are not the audience. Use it as
    evidence on your site, not as your growth plan.
  </p>
  <h3>Are architecture awards worth it?</h3>
  <p>
    Same answer. Excellent proof, a nice wall, and a strong line in a proposal. Enter the ones
    a buyer would recognize, put them where prospects can see them, and do not mistake a trophy
    for a booked project.
  </p>
  <h3>Isn't all press good press?</h3>
  <p>
    Coverage your buyer never sees mostly flatters your ego and your standing among peers.
    Coverage your buyer can find when they check you out helps you get hired. Both feel like
    press. Only one of them shows up in your calendar, so aim for the second.
  </p>

  <h2>Use press as proof, not as a plan</h2>
  <p>
    Press is borrowed credibility, and aimed right it is genuinely valuable. Aimed at your
    peers it is a lovely photo for the office wall. Aimed as proof behind an engine that
    actually reaches the people who hire you, it turns interested strangers into buyers who
    already half-trust you before the first call.
  </p>
  <p>
    Building that engine, and giving your proof somewhere useful to sit, is the part we run for
